      whence the claim.

Let X be a smooth and proper algebraic variety, and Y a smooth divisor in X. Let j be the inclusion of U=X\setminus Y into X. We have that \mathrm {R}^i j_*\mathbb {Z}=0 for i\neq 0,1, and the Leray spectral sequence for j can be identified with the long exact sequence of cohomology
446hodge-theory-iii-9.2.1.1hodge-theory-iii-9.2.1.1.xmlEquation9.2.1.1hodge-theory-iii-9.2.1 \ldots \to \operatorname {H}_Y^n(X) \to \operatorname {H}^n(X) \to \operatorname {H}^n(U) \xrightarrow {\partial } \ldots \tag{9.2.1.1}
with \operatorname {H}_Y^n(X) = \operatorname {H}^{n-2}(Y,\operatorname {\mathscr {H}}_Y^2).

For a reason that was made clear in , we identify \operatorname {\mathscr {H}}_Y^2 with the constant sheaf \mathbb {Z}(-1)_\mathbb {Z}. Since the Leray spectral sequence for j converges, by definition, to the mixed Hodge structure of \operatorname {H}^n(U), we find that the exact sequence
447hodge-theory-iii-9.2.1.2hodge-theory-iii-9.2.1.2.xmlEquation9.2.1.2hodge-theory-iii-9.2.1 \ldots \to \operatorname {H}^{n-2}(Y,\mathbb {Z})(-1) \to \operatorname {H}^n(X,\mathbb {Z}) \to \operatorname {H}^n(U,\mathbb {Z}) \xrightarrow {\partial } \ldots \tag{9.2.1.2}
is an exact sequence of mixed Hodge structures.

The Leray spectral sequence for j is also the spectral sequence of the filtered complex (\Omega _X^\bullet (\log  Y),W);
    the exact sequence above can thus also be identified with that induced by the short exact sequence

    448hodge-theory-iii-9.2.1.3hodge-theory-iii-9.2.1.3.xmlEquation9.2.1.3hodge-theory-iii-9.2.1         0         \to  \Omega _X^\bullet          \to  \Omega _X^\bullet (\log  Y)         \xrightarrow {\operatorname {Res}} \Omega _Y^\bullet          \to  0.       \tag{9.2.1.3}       

    For this reason, the homomorphism \partial  in  is also called the residue operator.

The residue operator
450hodge-theory-iii-9.2.2.1hodge-theory-iii-9.2.2.1.xmlEquation9.2.2.1hodge-theory-iii-9.2.2 \operatorname {Res}\colon \operatorname {H}^{n+1}(U,\mathbb {Z}) \to \operatorname {H}^n(Y,\mathbb {Z})(-1) \tag{9.2.2.1}
is strictly compatible with the Hodge filtration. The Hodge filtration of \operatorname {H}^n(U,\mathbb {C}) thus determines that of \operatorname {Ker}(\operatorname {H}^n(Y,\mathbb {C}))\to \operatorname {H}^{n+2}(X,\mathbb {C}).

The coskeleton functors exist if finite projective limits exist in \mathscr {C};
    the relative coskeleton functors exist if fibred products do;
    we have
           \operatorname {cosq}_k^Y(X)       = \operatorname {cosq}_k(X) \times _{\operatorname {cosq}_k\operatorname {sq}_k(Y)}Y.

The data of a u-morphism f from G to F consists of the data of, for each pair of opens (U\subset  X,V\subset  Y) such that u(U)\subset  V, a map f_{UV}\colon  G(V)\to  F(U);
    these maps must satisfy the condition

    2204hodge-theory-iii-5.1.5.starhodge-theory-iii-5.1.5.star.xmlCondition*hodge-theory-iii-5.1.5
